3. CREATE app/core/permission_cache.py

   A tiny in-memory cache module. Pure Python dict + threading.Lock.
   Do NOT use Redis or any external dependency.

   Exports:
     - cache_get(key: str) -> Optional[Any]
         Returns cached value if present and not expired, else None.
     - cache_set(key: str, value: Any, ttl_seconds: int = 300) -> None
         Stores value with expiry timestamp.
     - cache_clear() -> None
         Empties the cache.

   Implementation:
     _cache: Dict[str, Tuple[Any, float]]  # value, expiry_epoch
     _lock: threading.Lock

     On every get, check if expiry_epoch < time.time() → if so,
     remove entry and return None.

     Default TTL: 300 seconds (5 minutes). Caller can override.

     The cache is process-local. If the app runs multiple worker
     processes, each has its own cache. This is acceptable for
     current scale.

   Add a module-level docstring noting:
     "Process-local permission cache. 5-minute TTL. Cache entries
      expire naturally; there is no manual invalidation endpoint
      in this task. Admin workstream (post Task 4) will add a
      proper invalidation API."

