7. UPDATE ARCHITECTURE_DECISIONS.md

   Add Decision 13: Two-gate permission model.
     **Context:** Permissions need to be checked at both the route
       boundary (coarse, fast) and inside the workflow (fine-grained,
       after intent classification).
     **Decision:** Gate 1 checks module-level access at the route.
       Gate 2 checks agent-level access inside the workflow.
     **Why this is better:** Short-circuits unauthorized module
       requests before any LLM call. Defense in depth: a user
       cannot bypass module restrictions by manipulating their
       request even if intent classification picks an unauthorized
       agent.
     **Trade-offs:** Two DB queries instead of one for authorized
       requests. Mitigated by caching (Decision 14).
     **Alternatives considered:**
       - Single gate at agent level: rejected because it wastes
         LLM compute on requests that will be denied.
       - Single gate at module level: rejected because intent
         classification could pick agents the user doesn't have.

   Add Decision 14: Process-local permission cache with TTL.
     **Context:** Adding DB queries on every chat request would
       slow the system. Caching the result avoids redundant queries
       for repeated requests from the same user to the same module.
     **Decision:** In-memory Python dict with 5-minute TTL,
       protected by threading.Lock. No external dependency.
     **Why this is better:** Trivial to implement, zero ops
       overhead, sub-millisecond cache hits. TTL is short enough
       that permission changes propagate within 5 minutes naturally.
     **Trade-offs:** Cache is process-local — if app scales to
       multiple workers, each has its own cache (5-min skew possible
       across workers). No manual invalidation — admins changing
       permissions must wait up to 5 minutes for the change to be
       visible.
     **Alternatives considered:**
       - Redis: rejected as overkill for current scale.
       - No cache: rejected as wasteful for hot-path queries.
       - Invalidation endpoint: deferred to admin workstream.

